doc.ContractDescription: THE PROPOSED RESEARCH PROGRAM AIMS TO EXPERIMENTALLY STUDY THE PHENOMENON OF ICE CRYSTAL IMPINGEMENT, BREAKUP AND MELTING BY SIMULATING THE CONDITIONS WHERE CRYSTALS INTERACT WITH THE FLOW, ROTOR, STATOR AND FLOW PATH URFACES IN A GAS TURBINE COMPRESSOR. IT IS VERY DIFFICULT TO STUDY THESE IN A REAL COMPRESSOR DUE TO THE VARIABILITY IN THE FLOW, CRYSTAL THERMAL EFFECTS AND SHORT RESIDENCE TIME INVOLVED. AN ICE CRYSTAL TESTING RIG IS DESIRABLE TO HELP IN UNDERSTANDING THE ICING PHYSICS FOR THE UNIQUE ENGINE ICING PHENOMENON. THE PROPOSED APPROACH CONTROLS THE INITIAL CRYSTAL PROPERTIES SUCH AS SIZE, MELTING PERCENTAGE OF WATER, AND CRYSTAL VELOCITY. THE IMPACT MECHANICS OF THE CONDITIONED CRYSTAL, SUCH AS THE CRYSTAL IMPACT ANGLE AND TARGET SURFACE TEMPERATURE, ARE MEASURED IN A WIND TUNNEL. IT IS RECOGNIZED THAT THE WIND TUNNEL CANNOT TRULY SIMULATE THE FLOW DYNAMICS IN A COMPRESSOR. EFFORTS ARE CONCENTRATED ON THE KEY PHYSICAL CORRELATIONS BETWEEN CRYSTAL MELTED STATE, IMPACT AND REBOUND MECHANICS, ACCRETION AND SHEDDING. THESE CORRELATIONS ARE PRE-REQUISITE TO THE DEVELOPMENT OF PRACTICAL ICE CRYSTAL AERO-THERMAL MODELS FOR THE GAS TURBINE APPLICATIONS. THE PROPOSED THREE-YEAR EFFORT IS DISTRIBUTED AS FOLLOWS: I) YEAR 1- RIG DEVELOPMENT TO EFFECT CRYSTAL FREEZING&MELTING II) YEAR 2- DEVELOPMENT OF ICE CRYSTAL DYNAMICS TEST FACILITY III) YEAR 3 - CRYSTAL IMPACT DYNAMICS TESTING THE MAIN EFFORT IN YEAR 1 INVOLVES THE GENERATION OF A CONTROLLABLE SIZE WATER DROPLET, FREEZING AND MELTING OF A SINGLE ICE CRYSTAL, AND ALSO THE DEVELOPMENT OF A TECHNIQUE TO QUANTIFY THE AMOUNT OF MELT WATER IN A CRYSTAL. YEAR 2 EFFORT INVOLVES THE DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF A VERTICAL WIND TUNNEL TO ACCELERATE THE CRYSTAL AND TO IMPINGE IT ON A TARGET SURFACE. DATA COLLECTION WILL BE PERFORMED IN THE LAST YEAR. ONE KEY PHYSICAL PARAMETER BEING CONTROLLED IN ALL THESE EFFORTS IS THE USE OF MONO-DISPERSED (SINGLED-SIZE) WATER DROPLETS, WHICH MINIMIZES A SIGNIFICANT VARIABILITY IN THE TEST. SIGNIFICANT CHALLENGES ARE ANTICIPATED IN THE DETERMINATION OF THE MELT WATER PERCENTAGE AND MEASUREMENT OF THE CRYSTAL BOUNCE DIRECTION AND BREAKUP SIZES. IT IS ENVISIONED THAT SEVERAL ON-GOING ICE CRYSTAL RESEARCH EFFORTS WOULD BENEFIT FROM THE PROPOSED EXPERIMENTAL ICE CRYSTAL INVESTIGATION. THE EFFORT WILL ALSO PROVIDE EXPERIMENTAL DATA FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF CRYSTAL AERO-THERMAL AND ACCRETION MODELS.
